{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17569442","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17569442"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T00:28:08+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T00:28:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22196"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"22196","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/22196"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.12,0.24,0.18,0.01,0.46]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"15153"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107962"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"15153","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/15153"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22196"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90375"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"147"},{"type":"tags","id":"483"},{"type":"tags","id":"1142"},{"type":"tags","id":"1177"},{"type":"tags","id":"1787"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"5072"},{"type":"tags","id":"5076"},{"type":"tags","id":"11505"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"12920"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"39856"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40271"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43759"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107962","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/107962"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 68-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic for follow-up one week after discharge from hospital. He was admitted with an acute exacerbation of chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD) requiring five days of inpatient treatment. He has a 40 pack-year smoking history and quit two weeks ago. He has a medical history of asthma diagnosed in childhood and COPD. He does not take any regular medications. He works as a retired carpenter. On examination, he appears well but remains breathless on minimal exertion. His pulse rate is 88/min, blood pressure 135/80 mmHg, respiratory rate 20/min, SpO2 94% on room air, and temperature 36.5\u00b0C. Chest examination reveals reduced air entry bilaterally with scattered expiratory wheeze. Investigations reveal: haemoglobin 145 g/L (130-170), white cell count 8.2 \u00d7 10\u2079/L (4.0-11.0), eosinophils 0.35 \u00d7 10\u2079/L (0.04-0.40), C-reactive protein 12 mg/L (\u003C10).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Ctable\u003E\u003Ctr\u003E\u003Cth\u003ESpirometry\u003C/th\u003E\u003Cth\u003EResult\u003C/th\u003E\u003Cth\u003E% Predicted\u003C/th\u003E\u003C/tr\u003E\u003Ctr\u003E\u003Ctd\u003EFEV1\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd\u003E1.2 L\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd\u003E40%\u003C/td\u003E\u003C/tr\u003E\u003Ctr\u003E\u003Ctd\u003EFVC\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd\u003E2.8 L\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd\u003E70%\u003C/td\u003E\u003C/tr\u003E\u003Ctr\u003E\u003Ctd\u003EFEV1/FVC ratio\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd\u003E0.43\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd\u003E\u003C/td\u003E\u003C/tr\u003E\u003C/table\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial medication?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Long-acting muscarinic antagonist alone","Long-acting muscarinic antagonist/long-acting beta-agonist combination","Long-acting muscarinic antagonist/inhaled corticosteroid combination","Prolonged course of oral azithromycin","Long-acting muscarinic antagonist/long-acting beta-agonist/inhaled corticosteroid combination"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has COPD with severe airflow limitation (FEV1 40% predicted) and has just been hospitalised for an acute exacerbation. He remains significantly symptomatic with breathlessness on minimal exertion. Importantly, his blood eosinophil count is 350 cells/\u03bcL (0.35 \u00d7 10\u2079/L), which is above the threshold of 300 cells/\u03bcL. This elevated eosinophil count, combined with his recent hospitalisation for an exacerbation and history of asthma, indicates he would benefit from triple therapy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELong-acting muscarinic antagonist/long-acting beta-agonist/inhaled corticosteroid combination\u003C/strong\u003E (triple therapy) is the most appropriate initial treatment. The elevated blood eosinophils predict a good response to inhaled corticosteroids, and studies have shown that triple therapy reduces exacerbation risk more effectively than dual bronchodilator therapy in patients with eosinophils \u003E300 cells/\u03bcL who have had recent exacerbations. Triple therapy is recommended in several scenarios: (1) patients with frequent exacerbations (\u22652 moderate or \u22651 severe requiring hospitalisation in the past year) despite dual therapy, (2) patients with blood eosinophils \u2265300 cells/\u03bcL who have exacerbations despite LAMA or LABA monotherapy, (3) patients with features of asthma-COPD overlap, and (4) patients who remain symptomatic on dual bronchodilator therapy with elevated eosinophils.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELong-acting muscarinic antagonist/long-acting beta-agonist combination\u003C/strong\u003E would be appropriate for patients without elevated eosinophils or without a recent severe exacerbation. However, this patient meets criteria for triple therapy given his eosinophil count, recent hospitalisation, and asthma history.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELong-acting muscarinic antagonist/inhaled corticosteroid combination\u003C/strong\u003E provides anti-inflammatory therapy with ICS but lacks the additional bronchodilation from a LABA. While ICS is indicated given the elevated eosinophils, dual bronchodilator therapy is preferred in severe COPD, making triple therapy the better choice.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELong-acting muscarinic antagonist alone\u003C/strong\u003E would be inadequate monotherapy for this patient with severe disease, recent hospitalisation, and elevated eosinophils. Current guidelines recommend more intensive therapy in such cases.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProlonged course of oral azithromycin\u003C/strong\u003E is used in COPD for its anti-inflammatory and antimicrobial properties to reduce exacerbations. However, it is typically reserved for patients who continue to have exacerbations despite optimal inhaled therapy, not as initial treatment. Additionally, azithromycin requires baseline ECG assessment for QT prolongation and is contraindicated in some patients.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe relatively normal inflammatory markers (CRP 12 mg/L) suggest the acute exacerbation has resolved, but the persistent symptoms, elevated eosinophils, and asthma history support the need for triple therapy to prevent future exacerbations and improve symptom control.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Patients with COPD who have blood eosinophils \u003E300 cells/\u03bcL and remain symptomatic after hospitalisation benefit from triple therapy (LAMA/LABA/ICS).","Blood eosinophil count helps predict response to inhaled corticosteroids in COPD patients with exacerbation history.","Triple therapy reduces exacerbation risk more than dual bronchodilator therapy in patients with elevated eosinophils."],"references":["Global Initiative for Chronic Obstructive Lung Disease. Global Strategy for the Diagnosis, Management, and Prevention of Chronic Obstructive Pulmonary Disease: 2025 Report. Global Initiative for Chronic Obstructive Lung Disease; 2024. Available at: https://goldcopd.org/2025-gold-report/","Lung Foundation Australia. The COPD-X Plan: Australian and New Zealand Guidelines for the management of Chronic Obstructive Pulmonary Disease 2024. Version 2.77. Yang IA, George J, McDonald CF, Disler R, Ordman R, Goodwin A, Smith B, McNamara R, Zwar N, Dabscheck E, authors. Milton (QLD): Lung Foundation Australia; December 2024. Available from: https://copdx.org.au/copd-x-plan/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90375"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22196"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90375","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/90375"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-05T12:07:06+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-05T12:09:04+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"15153"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107962"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"me